I. File System & Management
Command Description
pwd Print working directory.
ls List directory contents.
mv <old-name> <new-name> Rename a file or folder.
cp <src-path> <dest-path> Copy a file.
cp -r <src-dir> <dest-dir> Copy a directory recursively.
nano <filename> Open a file in the nano editor.
cd <directory-name> Change directory.
tar Archiving multiple files.
zip <filename.zip> <file1> <file2> Compress files into a zip archive.
unzip <filename.zip> Extract files from a zip archive.
gzip <filename> Compress a file using gzip.
gunzip <filename> Decompress a file using gzip.
df -h To see the disk usage in a human-readable
format.
du -h How much disk is used in a human-readable
format.
free -h To show memory usage in a human-readable
format.
fdisk -l To list all storage devices
